label: pennait
etymology: a learned formation from Lat. poenitere or poenitentia (see Thurn. Hdb. 517 , Pedersen Vgl. Gr. i 213)

label: coibdelach
etymology: denominative (adjectival): eDIL suggest that this is derived from coibdil (compound: prefix com- + feidil)

label: foircenn
etymology: *uφer-ku̯enno-; older compound in Milan forcan from *uφer-ku̯enn-o-

label: forcan
etymology: *uφer-ku̯enno-; older compound in Milan forcan from *uφer-ku̯enn-o-

label: cétbuid
etymology: *kintu-buti-; vn. of ceta·bí;*kanta-bu-ti; vn. of ceta·bí

label: aille
etymology: < Latin: < allelūia [?] (see also Vendryes, Lex.) < Hebrew: הַלְּלוּיָהּ

label: martrae
etymology: < Lat. martyrium but formed on the base of Ir. martar

label: soilse
etymology: denominative (abstract): < solus (adjective prefix so-/su- + the root of lés, compare dolus)

label: gabál
etymology: *gabaglā- (influenced by *kaglā- cf. Schumacher 2000: 205); vn. of gaibid

label: gabáil
etymology: *gabaglā- (influenced by *kaglā- cf. Schumacher 2000: 205); vn. of gaibid

label: lann
etymology: < Latin: lāmina; but see Ériu xxvi 175

label: aincride
etymology: compound of the negative prefix an- and cride

label: béscnae
etymology: The eDIL (s.v. bésgnae) claims that this is a compound of bés 1 and gné. But this seems unlikely to be the whole story, since gné is a neuter s-stem, not an i̯o-stem. Some restructuring must have occurred, or there were two nouns gné formed from the same root with different stem classes.

label: méit
etymology: *mantī-; méit was originally an ī-stem, which at some point became an ā-stem mét, with the (occasional) possiblity to have dative/accusative mét.

label: mét
etymology: *mantī-; méit was originally an ī-stem, which at some point became an ā-stem mét, with the (occasional) possiblity to have dative/accusative mét.

label: incholnugud
etymology: denominative < colainn; calque on Lat. in-carn-atio; vn. of **incholnaigidir

label: coibdelach
etymology: denominative (adjectival): eDIL suggest that this is derived from coibdil (compound: prefix com- + feidil)

label: comnesam
etymology: Compound of com- and the superlative of ocus 1.

label: cimbid
etymology: *kimbi-ti-? ; denominative (+ agent suffix -(th)(a)id): cimm (LEIA) or *kamb-i̯ato- ‘crooked person’ (i.e. bent over in fetters) (David Stifter, p.c.)

label: preiceptóir
etymology: agent suffix -(e)óir: < Latin praeceptor but with a shift of suffix.
